QuestionTxt: If you had to choose, which presidential candidate do you find to be more energetic?...Donald Trump, Joe Biden
QuestionNote: * = Less than .5 percent. This question was asked as part of a survey designed by students in an advanced undergraduate course, Govt/Comm 3189, to help them gain a better understanding of creating and conducting academic research studies. The questions included a wide variety of topics including healthcare, government, and media. Each student was able to submit one question that was relevant to their personal research interests. The survey was administered by web mode and by phone mode by NORC at the University of Chicago. Respondents were randomly assigned to one of two conditions for this question and its counterpart. Based on this assignment, these questions were framed in terms of either truthful or energetic.
SubPopulation: Asked of respondents randomly assigned to receive the "energetic" condition (N = 539)
SurveySponsor: Enns, Peter K. and Jonathon P. Schuldt, Cornell University
SourceDoc: 2020 Taking Americas Pulse Survey, Designed by Students at Cornell
IntMethod: Computer-Assisted telephone interview (CATI); Web-based survey

QuestionTxt: (Who do you plan to vote for in the 2020 election for president?...Joe Biden, the Democrat, Donald Trump, the Republican, another candidate, undecided, probably not vote) (If Another candidate/Undecided/Probably not vote/Don't know/Skipped on web/Refused, ask:) As for today, do you lean more toward Joe Biden, the Democrat, Donald Trump, the Republican or neither?
QuestionNote: * = Less than .5 percent.  This question was asked as part of a survey designed by students in an advanced undergraduate course, Govt/Comm 3189, to help them gain a better understanding of creating and conducting academic research studies. The questions included a wide variety of topics including healthcare, government, and media. Each student was able to submit one question that was relevant to their personal research interests. The survey was administered by web mode and by phone mode by NORC at the University of Chicago.
SubPopulation: Asked of those who said they would vote for another candidate in the 2020 presidential election, were undecided, probably would not vote, didn't know, skipped on web, or refused (N = 203)
SurveySponsor: Enns, Peter K. and Jonathon P. Schuldt, Cornell University
SourceDoc: 2020 Taking Americas Pulse Survey, Designed by Students at Cornell
IntMethod: Computer-Assisted telephone interview (CATI); Web-based survey

QuestionTxt: (Who do you plan to vote for in the 2020 election for president?...Joe Biden, the Democrat, Donald Trump, the Republican, another candidate, undecided, probably not vote) (If Another candidate/Undecided/Probably not vote/Don't know/Skipped on web/Refused, ask:) As for today, do you lean more toward Joe Biden, the Democrat, Donald Trump, the Republican or neither?

This question was asked as part of a survey designed by students in an advanced undergraduate course, Govt/Comm 3189, to help them gain a better understanding of creating and conducting academic research studies. The questions included a wide variety of topics including healthcare, government, and media. Each student was able to submit one question that was relevant to their personal research interests. The survey was administered by web mode and by phone mode by NORC at the University of Chicago.

QuestionTxt: If you had to choose, which presidential candidate do you find to be more truthful?...Donald Trump, Joe Biden
QuestionNote: * = Less than .5 percent. This question was asked as part of a survey designed by students in an advanced undergraduate course, Govt/Comm 3189, to help them gain a better understanding of creating and conducting academic research studies. The questions included a wide variety of topics including healthcare, government, and media. Each student was able to submit one question that was relevant to their personal research interests. The survey was administered by web mode and by phone mode by NORC at the University of Chicago. Respondents were randomly assigned to one of two conditions for this question and its counterpart. Based on this assignment, these questions were framed in terms of either truthful or energetic.
SubPopulation: Asked of respondents randomly assigned to receive the "truthful" condition (N = 620)
SurveySponsor: Enns, Peter K. and Jonathon P. Schuldt, Cornell University
SourceDoc: 2020 Taking Americas Pulse Survey, Designed by Students at Cornell
IntMethod: Computer-Assisted telephone interview (CATI); Web-based survey

SubPopulation: Asked of those who ranked this as a top three problem (N = 691)
SourceDoc: VP debate improves views of Harris
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: If the 2020 presidential election were being held today, would you vote for Donald Trump the Republican candidate, Joe Biden the Democrat candidate, Jo Jorgensen the Libertarian candidate, or Howie Hawkins the Green Party candidate? (If Neither/Other/Don't know/Refused, ask:) As of today, do you lean more toward Trump, more toward Biden, more toward Jorgensen, or more toward Hawkins?
QuestionNote: * = Less than .5 percent.  Hawkins only included where on the ballot.
SurveySponsor: Pew Research Center for the People & the Press
SourceDoc: Amid Campaign Turmoil, Biden Holds Wide Leads on Coronavirus, Unifying the Country
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The American Trends Panel (ATP), created by Pew Research Center, is a nationally representative panel of randomly selected US adults recruited from landline and cellphone random-digit-dial surveys. Panelists participate via monthly self-administered web surveys. Panelists who do not have Internet access are provided with a tablet and wireless Internet connection. The ATP is managed by Ipsos.

QuestionTxt: Regardless of who you support, which (2020 presidential) candidate do you trust to do a better job of handling...Supreme Court nominations?...Joe Biden, Donald Trump, both equally, neither
SurveyOrg: AP-NORC Center for Public Affairs Research
SourceDoc: Voters see the nation as fundamentally divided
IntMethod: Telephone Interview; Web-based survey
StudyNote: Interviews were conducted both online using a self-administered design and by telephone using live interviewers. All interviews were conducted among participants in AmeriSpeak, a probability-based panel designed to be representative of the national US adult population run by NORC at the University of Chicago. Panel participants without Internet access were interviewed via telephone by professional interviewers under the direction of NORC. NORC's AmeriSpeak Panel provides a representative panel of civilian, non-institutional adults (age 18 and over) living in the United States.

SubPopulation: Asked of those who ranked this as a top three problem (N = 175)
SourceDoc: VP debate improves views of Harris
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

SubPopulation: Asked of those who ranked this as a top three problem (N = 409)
SourceDoc: VP debate improves views of Harris
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: Regardless of who you support, which (2020 presidential) candidate do you trust to do a better job of handling...the coronavirus outbreak?...Joe Biden, Donald Trump, both equally, neither
SurveyOrg: AP-NORC Center for Public Affairs Research
SourceDoc: Voters see the nation as fundamentally divided
IntMethod: Telephone Interview; Web-based survey
StudyNote: Interviews were conducted both online using a self-administered design and by telephone using live interviewers. All interviews were conducted among participants in AmeriSpeak, a probability-based panel designed to be representative of the national US adult population run by NORC at the University of Chicago. Panel participants without Internet access were interviewed via telephone by professional interviewers under the direction of NORC. NORC's AmeriSpeak Panel provides a representative panel of civilian, non-institutional adults (age 18 and over) living in the United States.

SubPopulation: Asked of those who ranked this as a top three problem (N = 367)
SourceDoc: VP debate improves views of Harris
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

SourceDoc: Voters see the nation as fundamentally divided
IntMethod: Telephone Interview; Web-based survey
StudyNote: Interviews were conducted both online using a self-administered design and by telephone using live interviewers. All interviews were conducted among participants in AmeriSpeak, a probability-based panel designed to be representative of the national US adult population run by NORC at the University of Chicago. Panel participants without Internet access were interviewed via telephone by professional interviewers under the direction of NORC. NORC's AmeriSpeak Panel provides a representative panel of civilian, non-institutional adults (age 18 and over) living in the United States.

QuestionTxt: Regardless of how you intend to vote, which (2020) presidential ticket do you think is better on each of your 3 top issues?...Joe Biden/Kamala Harris, Donald Trump/Mike Pence...Violent crime
SubPopulation: Asked of those who ranked this as a top three problem (N = 338)
SourceDoc: VP debate improves views of Harris
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: (Regardless of how you intend to vote, which (2020) presidential ticket do you think is better on each of your 3 top issues?...Joe Biden/Kamala Harris, Donald Trump/Mike Pence)...Abortion
SubPopulation: Asked of those who ranked this as a top three problem (N = 224)
SourceDoc: Pre-VP debate: Small advantage for Harris
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: Regardless of who you support, which (2020 presidential) candidate do you trust to do a better job of handling...the economy?...Joe Biden, Donald Trump, both equally, neither
SurveyOrg: AP-NORC Center for Public Affairs Research
SourceDoc: Voters see the nation as fundamentally divided
IntMethod: Telephone Interview; Web-based survey
StudyNote: Interviews were conducted both online using a self-administered design and by telephone using live interviewers. All interviews were conducted among participants in AmeriSpeak, a probability-based panel designed to be representative of the national US adult population run by NORC at the University of Chicago. Panel participants without Internet access were interviewed via telephone by professional interviewers under the direction of NORC. NORC's AmeriSpeak Panel provides a representative panel of civilian, non-institutional adults (age 18 and over) living in the United States.

SubPopulation: Asked of those who ranked this as a top three problem (N = 778)
SourceDoc: Pre-VP debate: Small advantage for Harris
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: Who do you plan to vote for in the 2020 election for president?...Joe Biden, the Democrat, Donald Trump, the Republican, another candidate, probably not vote...As of today, do you lean more toward Biden or Trump?
SurveyOrg: AP-NORC Center for Public Affairs Research
SourceDoc: Voters see the nation as fundamentally divided
IntMethod: Telephone Interview; Web-based survey
StudyNote: Interviews were conducted both online using a self-administered design and by telephone using live interviewers. All interviews were conducted among participants in AmeriSpeak, a probability-based panel designed to be representative of the national US adult population run by NORC at the University of Chicago. Panel participants without Internet access were interviewed via telephone by professional interviewers under the direction of NORC. NORC's AmeriSpeak Panel provides a representative panel of civilian, non-institutional adults (age 18 and over) living in the United States.

Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: (Regardless of how you intend to vote, which (2020 presidential) candidate do you think is better on each of your 3 top issues?...Joe Biden, Donald Trump)...The COVID-19 or coronavirus outbreak
SubPopulation: Asked of those in wave 1 who named this issue (N = 1699)
SourceDoc: Who Won The First 2020 Presidential Debate?
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: Wave 1 of the survey was conducted September 21-28, 2020 (N=3133). Wave 2 respondents were re-interviewed September 29-30, 2020 (N=1827). The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

SourceDoc: Who Won The First 2020 Presidential Debate?
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: Wave 1 of the survey was conducted September 21-28, 2020 (N=3133). Wave 2 respondents were re-interviewed September 29-30, 2020 (N=1827). The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: (Regardless of how you intend to vote, which (2020 presidential) candidate do you think is better on each of your 3 top issues?...Joe Biden, Donald Trump)...Racial inequality
SubPopulation: Asked of those in wave 2 who named this issue (N = 457)
SourceDoc: Who Won The First 2020 Presidential Debate?
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: Wave 1 of the survey was conducted September 21-28, 2020 (N=3133). Wave 2 respondents were re-interviewed September 29-30, 2020 (N=1827). The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: (Regardless of how you intend to vote, which (2020 presidential) candidate do you think is better on each of your 3 top issues?...Joe Biden, Donald Trump)...Economic inequality
SubPopulation: Asked of those in wave 2 who named this issue (N = 263)
SourceDoc: Who Won The First 2020 Presidential Debate?
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: Wave 1 of the survey was conducted September 21-28, 2020 (N=3133). Wave 2 respondents were re-interviewed September 29-30, 2020 (N=1827). The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: (Regardless of how you intend to vote, which (2020 presidential) candidate do you think is better on each of your 3 top issues?...Joe Biden, Donald Trump)...Abortion
SubPopulation: Asked of those in wave 2 who named this issue (N = 170)
SourceDoc: Who Won The First 2020 Presidential Debate?
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: Wave 1 of the survey was conducted September 21-28, 2020 (N=3133). Wave 2 respondents were re-interviewed September 29-30, 2020 (N=1827). The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: (Regardless of how you intend to vote, which (2020 presidential) candidate do you think is better on each of your 3 top issues?...Joe Biden, Donald Trump)...Health care
SubPopulation: Asked of those in wave 1 who named this issue (N = 1149)
SourceDoc: Who Won The First 2020 Presidential Debate?
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: Wave 1 of the survey was conducted September 21-28, 2020 (N=3133). Wave 2 respondents were re-interviewed September 29-30, 2020 (N=1827). The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: (Regardless of how you intend to vote, which (2020 presidential) candidate do you think is better on each of your 3 top issues?...Joe Biden, Donald Trump)...The COVID-19 or coronavirus outbreak
SubPopulation: Asked of those in wave 2 who named this issue (N = 997)
SourceDoc: Who Won The First 2020 Presidential Debate?
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: Wave 1 of the survey was conducted September 21-28, 2020 (N=3133). Wave 2 respondents were re-interviewed September 29-30, 2020 (N=1827). The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: (Regardless of how you intend to vote, which (2020 presidential) candidate do you think is better on each of your 3 top issues?...Joe Biden, Donald Trump)...Education
SubPopulation: Asked of those in wave 1 who named this issue (N = 432)
SourceDoc: Who Won The First 2020 Presidential Debate?
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: Wave 1 of the survey was conducted September 21-28, 2020 (N=3133). Wave 2 respondents were re-interviewed September 29-30, 2020 (N=1827). The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: (Regardless of how you intend to vote, which (2020 presidential) candidate do you think is better on each of your 3 top issues?...Joe Biden, Donald Trump)...Gun policy
SubPopulation: Asked of those in wave 2 who named this issue (N = 153)
SourceDoc: Who Won The First 2020 Presidential Debate?
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: Wave 1 of the survey was conducted September 21-28, 2020 (N=3133). Wave 2 respondents were re-interviewed September 29-30, 2020 (N=1827). The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: (Regardless of how you intend to vote, which (2020 presidential) candidate do you think is better on each of your 3 top issues?...Joe Biden, Donald Trump)...Economic inequality
SubPopulation: Asked of those in wave 1 who named this issue (N = 416)
SourceDoc: Who Won The First 2020 Presidential Debate?
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: Wave 1 of the survey was conducted September 21-28, 2020 (N=3133). Wave 2 respondents were re-interviewed September 29-30, 2020 (N=1827). The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: (Regardless of how you intend to vote, which (2020 presidential) candidate do you think is better on each of your 3 top issues?...Joe Biden, Donald Trump)...Other
SubPopulation: Asked of those in wave 1 who named this issue
SourceDoc: Who Won The First 2020 Presidential Debate?
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: Wave 1 of the survey was conducted September 21-28, 2020 (N=3133). Wave 2 respondents were re-interviewed September 29-30, 2020 (N=1827). The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: (Regardless of how you intend to vote, which (2020 presidential) candidate do you think is better on each of your 3 top issues?...Joe Biden, Donald Trump)...The economy
SubPopulation: Asked of those in wave 2 who named this issue (N = 920)
SourceDoc: Who Won The First 2020 Presidential Debate?
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: Wave 1 of the survey was conducted September 21-28, 2020 (N=3133). Wave 2 respondents were re-interviewed September 29-30, 2020 (N=1827). The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: Regardless of how you may vote, who do you think has more respect for those who serve in the United States military, Joe Biden or Donald Trump?
SourceDoc: Deep skepticism for Trump's coronavirus response endures
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: If the (2020) election for president were being held today, and the candidates were Joe Biden the Democrat and Donald Trump the Republican, for whom would you vote?...Joe Biden, Donald Trump, someone else, would not vote
SourceDoc: Conspiracy theories, misinformation, COVID-19, and the 2020 election
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: (For each of the following, please indicate whether the phrase best describes Donald Trump or Joe Biden.)...Would do a better job handling racial discrimination
SourceDoc: Trump's rhetoric on protests seen as detrimental by majority of Americans: POLL
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: If the (2020) election for president were being held today and the candidates were Joe Biden, the Democrat, Donald Trump, the Republican, Jo Jorgensen, the Libertarian, and Howie Hawkins, the Green Party, for whom would you vote?
SourceDoc: NEW MARQUETTE LAW SCHOOL POLL FINDS ALMOST HALF OF VOTERS NATIONWIDE RATE CHOICE OF NEXT SUPREME COURT JUSTICE AS VERY IMPORTANT
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: Interviews were conducted both online using a self-administered design and by telephone using live interviewers. All interviews were conducted among participants in AmeriSpeak, a probability-based panel designed to be representative of the national US adult population run by NORC at the University of Chicago. Panel participants without Internet access were interviewed via telephone by professional interviewers under the direction of NORC. NORC's AmeriSpeak Panel provides a representative panel of civilian, non-institutional adults (age 18 and over) living in the United States.

QuestionTxt: (For each of the following, please indicate whether the phrase best describes Donald Trump or Joe Biden.)...Would do more to unite Americans rather than divide them
SourceDoc: Trump's rhetoric on protests seen as detrimental by majority of Americans: POLL
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

SourceDoc: Trump's rhetoric on protests seen as detrimental by majority of Americans: POLL
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: If the (2020) election for president were being held today, and the candidates were Joe Biden the Democrat and Donald Trump the Republican, for whom would you vote?
SourceDoc: Socially distant: How our divided social networks explain our politics
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: Interviews were conducted both online using a self-administered design and by telephone using live interviewers. All interviews were conducted among participants in AmeriSpeak, a probability-based panel designed to be representative of the national US adult population run by NORC at the University of Chicago. Panel participants without Internet access were interviewed via telephone by professional interviewers under the direction of NORC. NORC's AmeriSpeak Panel provides a representative panel of civilian, non-institutional adults (age 18 and over) living in the United States.

IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: Interviews were conducted both online using a self-administered design and by telephone using live interviewers. All interviews were conducted among participants in AmeriSpeak, a probability-based panel designed to be representative of the national US adult population run by NORC at the University of Chicago. Panel participants without Internet access were interviewed via telephone by professional interviewers under the direction of NORC. NORC's AmeriSpeak Panel provides a representative panel of civilian, non-institutional adults (age 18 and over) living in the United States.

NORC's AmeriSpeak Panel provides a representative panel of civilian, non-institutional adults (age 18 and over) living in the United States.

NORC's AmeriSpeak Panel provides a representative panel of civilian, non-institutional adults (age 18 and over) living in the United States.

QuestionTxt: If the (2020) presidential election were held today, for whom would you vote if the candidates were Joe Biden, the Democrat or Donald Trump, the Republican?
SubPopulation: Black Americans, including an oversample of 1050 adult non-Hispanic Blacks (n=1170). Registered voters
SourceDoc: Black Americans say racism, policing top issues for November, favor Biden by huge margin, Post-Ipsos poll find
SampleDesc: National adult, including an oversample of 1050 adult non-Hispanic Blacks
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

SurveyOrg: The AP-NORC Center for Public Affairs Research
SourceDoc: Anxiety props up Biden, Trump voters fervent
IntMethod: Telephone Interview; Computer-Assisted telephone interview (CATI); Web-based survey
StudyNote: Interviews were conducted both online using a self-administered design and by telephone using live interviewers. All interviews were conducted among participants in AmeriSpeak, a probability-based panel designed to be representative of the national US adult population run by NORC at the University of Chicago. Panel participants without Internet access were interviewed via telephone by professional interviewers under the direction of NORC. NORC's AmeriSpeak Panel provides a representative panel of civilian, non-institutional adults (age 18 and over) living in the United States.

SubPopulation: Black Americans, including an oversample of 1050 adult non-Hispanic Blacks (n=1170)
SourceDoc: Black Americans say racism, policing top issues for November, favor Biden by huge margin, Post-Ipsos poll find
SampleDesc: National adult, including an oversample of 1050 adult non-Hispanic Blacks
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

SubPopulation: Black Americans, including an oversample of 1050 adult non-Hispanic Blacks (n=1170). Asked of Registered voters who support Biden (92% of Registered voters)
SourceDoc: Black Americans say racism, policing top issues for November, favor Biden by huge margin, Post-Ipsos poll find
SampleDesc: National adult, including an oversample of 1050 adult non-Hispanic Blacks
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: Do you believe, as president, Joe Biden would do a better job, a worse job, or about the same job of handling the coronavirus crisis as Donald Trump?
SurveyOrg: NORC at the University of Chicago
SourceDoc: The Coronavirus, the Election, and Daily Life
IntMethod: Telephone Interview; Web-based survey
StudyNote: Interviews were conducted both online using a self-administered design and by telephone using live interviewers. All interviews were conducted among participants in AmeriSpeak, a probability-based panel designed to be representative of the national US adult population run by NORC at the University of Chicago. Panel participants without Internet access were interviewed via telephone by professional interviewers under the direction of NORC. NORC's AmeriSpeak Panel provides a representative panel of civilian, non-institutional adults (age 18 and over) living in the United States.

QuestionTxt: Imagine the primary is over and each of the following candidates has won the Democratic nomination. What do you think their chances would be of defeating Donald Trump in November 2020? Use a scale of 0 to 100 with 0 meaning absolutely certain to lose to Trump and 100 meaning absolutely certain to defeat Trump. For each candidate enter a number from 0 to 100....Joe Biden
SourceDoc: Who Won The South Carolina Democratic Debate?
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: Based on what you know, do you believe the following did or did not happen?...President (Donald) Trump asked the government of Ukraine to investigate Joe and Hunter Biden
SourceDoc: Most Americans Think Theres Enough Evidence To Impeach Trump
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: Respondents were originally interviewed Nov. 13-18, 2019. The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: Based on what you know, if the following happened, would they be impeachable offenses or not impeachable offenses?...President (Donald) Trump asking the government of Ukraine to investigate Joe and Hunter Biden
SourceDoc: Our Poll Finds A Majority Of Americans Think The Evidence Supports Trumps Removal
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: Respondents were originally interviewed Nov. 13-18, 2019. The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: (Based on what you know, if the following happened, would they be impeachable offenses or not impeachable offenses?)...President (Donald) Trump withholding military aid from Ukraine unless the Ukrainians opened an investigation into the Bidens
SourceDoc: Our Poll Finds A Majority Of Americans Think The Evidence Supports Trumps Removal
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: Respondents were originally interviewed Nov. 13-18, 2019. The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

SourceDoc: Broad Support for Farmworker Protections in COVID-19 Context
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The survey was administered by distributing email invitations to stratified random samples of the states registered voters. Each email included an invitation for invited voters to participate in a nonpartisan survey and provided a link to the IGS website where the survey was housed. Reminder emails were distributed to non-responding voters and an opt out link was provided for voters not wishing to participate and not wanting to receive future emails from IGS about the survey.

StudyNote: Respondents were originally interviewed Nov. 13-18, 2019. The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: Respondents were originally interviewed Nov. 13-18, 2019. The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: If the 2020 presidential election were being held today, would you vote for Donald Trump, the Republican, Joe Biden, the Democrat, a third party candidate or would not vote?
SurveyOrg: NORC at the University of Chicago
SourceDoc: Hardship, anxiety, and optimism: Racial and partisan disparities in Americans response to COVID-19
IntMethod: Telephone Interview; Web-based survey
StudyNote: Interviews were conducted both online using a self-administered design and by telephone using live interviewers. All interviews were conducted among participants in AmeriSpeak, a probability-based panel designed to be representative of the national US adult population run by NORC at the University of Chicago. Panel participants without Internet access were interviewed via telephone by professional interviewers under the direction of NORC. NORC's AmeriSpeak Panel provides a representative panel of civilian, non-institutional adults (age 18 and over) living in the United States.

QuestionTxt: Based on what you know, if the following happened, would they be impeachable offenses or not impeachable offenses?...President (Donald) Trump asking the government of Ukraine to investigate Joe and Hunter Biden
SourceDoc: Most Americans Think Theres Enough Evidence To Impeach Trump
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: Respondents were originally interviewed Nov. 13-18, 2019. The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: (Based on what you know, if the following happened, would they be appropriate or inappropriate behaviors for a president?)...President (Donald) Trump withholding military aid from Ukraine unless the Ukrainians opened an investigation into the Bidens
SourceDoc: Most Americans Think Theres Enough Evidence To Impeach Trump
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: Respondents were originally interviewed Nov. 13-18, 2019. The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: If the November 2020 election were being held today, would you vote for Democrat Joe Biden or for Republican Donald Trump?
SurveyOrg: NORC at the University of Chicago
SourceDoc: The Coronavirus, the Election, and Daily Life
IntMethod: Telephone Interview; Web-based survey
StudyNote: Interviews were conducted both online using a self-administered design and by telephone using live interviewers. All interviews were conducted among participants in AmeriSpeak, a probability-based panel designed to be representative of the national US adult population run by NORC at the University of Chicago. Panel participants without Internet access were interviewed via telephone by professional interviewers under the direction of NORC. NORC's AmeriSpeak Panel provides a representative panel of civilian, non-institutional adults (age 18 and over) living in the United States.

SourceDoc: Biden holds wide lead among black voters in Democratic presidential race, Post-Ipsos poll finds
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: (Based on what you know, if the following happened, would they be appropriate or inappropriate behaviors for a president?)...President (Donald) Trump withholding military aid from Ukraine unless the Ukrainians opened an investigation into the Bidens
SourceDoc: The Impeachment Hearings Just Confirmed Voters Preexisting Opinions
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: Respondents were originally interviewed Nov. 13-18, 2019. The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

SubPopulation: Asked of those who chose a most important issue in determining their vote (99%)
SourceDoc: A Final Look At Who Won The Third Democratic Debate
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: Which of the following (2020) Democratic (presidential) candidates would you support instead of Donald Trump?...Bernie Sanders, Joe Biden, Elizabeth Warren, Cory Booker, Kamala Harris, Andrew Yang, Julian Castro, Tulsi Gabbard, Amy Klobuchar, Pete Buttigieg, Michael Bennet, Beto O'Rourke, Tim Ryan, Steve Bullock, John Delaney, Tom Steyer, Marianne Williamson, Wayne Messam, Joe Sestak
QuestionNote: Adds to more than 100% due to multiple responses.
SubPopulation: Asked of those whose vote for president will depend on who the Democratic candidate is (34%)
SourceDoc: Support for Impeaching President Trump and Removing Him From Office Increases Over the Last Month
IntMethod: Telephone Interview; Web-based survey
StudyNote: Note      Interviews were conducted both online using a self-administered design and by telephone using live interviewers. All interviews were conducted among participants in AmeriSpeak, a probability-based panel designed to be representative of the national US adult population run by NORC at the University of Chicago. Panel participants without Internet access were interviewed via telephone by professional interviewers under the direction of NORC. NORCs AmeriSpeak Panel provides a representative panel of civilian, non-institutional adults (age 18 and over) living in the United States.

QuestionTxt: Based on what you know, if the following happened, would they be appropriate or inappropriate behaviors for a president?...President (Donald) Trump asking the government of Ukraine to investigate Joe and Hunter Biden
SourceDoc: Most Americans Think Trump Committed An Impeachable Offense
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: How serious of a problem is it that President (Donald) Trump encouraged the Ukrainian president to investigate Joe Biden and his son, Hunter?...Very serious, somewhat serious, not so serious, not serious at all
SourceDoc: Only 17% of Americans surprised by Trump's actions tied to Ukraine
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: Respondents were shown a video of Joe Biden saying: "Obamacare is working. The way to build this and get to it immediately is to build on Obamacare. Go back and do, take back all the things that (Donald) Trump took away, provide a public option, meaning every single person in America would be able to buy another option if they didn't like their employer plan or if they're on Medicaid they would automatically be in the plan. It would be take place immediately and move quickly and it would ensure the vast, vast, vast majority of Americans." Do you find the argument in this video to be very convincing, somewhat convincing, not so convincing, or not convincing at all?
SourceDoc: Most Democratic voters say both Biden and Sanders made convincing health care arguments at debates

Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

SourceDoc: NEW NATIONWIDE MARQUETTE LAW SCHOOL POLL FINDS CONFIDENCE IN U.S. SUPREME COURT OVERALL, THOUGH MORE PRONOUNCED AMONG CONSERVATIVES
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: Interviews were conducted both online using a self-administered design and by telephone using live interviewers. All interviews were conducted among participants in AmeriSpeak, a probability-based panel designed to be representative of the national US adult population run by NORC at the University of Chicago. Panel participants without Internet access were interviewed via telephone by professional interviewers under the direction of NORC. NORC's AmeriSpeak Panel provides a representative panel of civilian, non-institutional adults (age 18 and over) living in the United States.

QuestionTxt: What do you think the following Democratic (presidential) candidates' chances are of defeating Donald Trump in November 2020? Use a scale of 0 to 100 with 0 meaning absolutely certain to lose to Trump and 100 meaning absolutely certain to defeat Trump. For each candidate enter a number from 0 to 100....Joe Biden
SourceDoc: A Final Look At Who Won The Third Democratic Debate
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: Based on what you know, if the following happened, would they be impeachable offenses or not impeachable offenses?...President (Donald) Trump asking the government of Ukraine to investigate Joe and Hunter Biden
SourceDoc: Most Americans Think Trump Committed An Impeachable Offense
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. QuestionTxt: Which of the following (2020 Democratic presidential) candidates do you believe is the best on your issue of ability to beat Donald Trump/climate change/crime/education/foreign affairs/gun policy/health care/immigration/jobs/wealth and income inequality/racism/Social Security/taxes/the economy/the makeup of the Supreme Court/sexism/the military/something else?...Joe Biden, Cory Booker, Pete Buttigieg, Julian Castro, Kamala Harris, Amy Klobuchar, Beto O'Rourke, Bernie Sanders, Elizabeth Warren, Andrew Yang, someone else
SubPopulation: Asked of hose who chose a most important issue in determining their vote (99%)
SourceDoc: The Third Debate Influenced Those Who Watched  But A Lot Of People Didnt
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: (Based on what you know, if the following happened, would they be impeachable offenses or not impeachable offenses?)...President (Donald) Trump withholding military aid from Ukraine unless the Ukrainians opened an investigation into the Bidens
SourceDoc: The Impeachment Hearings Just Confirmed Voters Preexisting Opinions
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: Respondents were originally interviewed Nov. 13-18, 2019. The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.

QuestionTxt: (Based on what you know, do you believe the following did or did not happen?)...President (Donald) Trump withheld military aid from Ukraine unless the Ukrainians opened an investigation into the Joe Bidens
SourceDoc: The Impeachment Hearings Just Confirmed Voters Preexisting Opinions
IntMethod: Web-based survey
StudyNote: Respondents were originally interviewed Nov. 13-18, 2019. The poll was fielded by Ipsos using its national KnowledgePanel. The KnowledgePanel is a nationally representative probability sample of the US adult population. Panelists are recruited by randomly selecting residential addresses using a process called address-based sampling (ABS). Since nearly 3-in-10 US households do not have home Internet access, respondent households who do not have Internet access or own a computer are provided Internet service and a netbook computer to ensure that panel respondents are representative of the US adult population. Unlike opt-in panels, households are not permitted to "self-select" into KnowledgePanel; nor are they allowed to participate in many surveys per week.
